::USGOV-U01-L03-Q01::What is power? {
~The public acceptance of a leader#Incorrect. That describes legitimacy, not power.
=The ability to influence or control people and decisions#Correct. Power is the ability to influence or control.
~The right to use authority only during elections#Incorrect. That does not define power.
~A list of citizen rights#Incorrect. Rights are not the same as power.
}

::USGOV-U01-L03-Q02::What is authority? {
=The recognized right to use power#Correct. Authority is accepted as the right to use power.
~The ability to ignore laws#Incorrect. Authority is not ignoring laws.
~Public disagreement with leaders#Incorrect. That does not define authority.
~The same thing as legitimacy#Incorrect. Authority and legitimacy are related but not identical.
}

::USGOV-U01-L03-Q03::What does legitimacy mean? {
~The government has no power#Incorrect. Legitimacy is not the absence of power.
~Citizens never question leaders#Incorrect. People may still question leaders even in legitimate systems.
=People believe the government’s authority is rightful#Correct. Legitimacy means authority is accepted as justified.
~Only one person makes all decisions#Incorrect. That describes a power arrangement, not legitimacy.
}

::USGOV-U01-L03-Q04::Why is legitimacy important? {
~It makes rules less clear#Incorrect. Legitimacy supports order and clarity, not confusion.
~It removes the need for laws#Incorrect. Legitimacy does not remove the need for laws.
~It prevents any disagreement in society#Incorrect. Disagreement can still happen even when legitimacy exists.
=It helps build trust and stability#Correct. Public acceptance of authority helps create stability.
}

::USGOV-U01-L03-Q05::What may happen if a government has power but lacks legitimacy? {
=Citizens may resist or refuse to cooperate#Correct. If authority is not accepted, resistance becomes more likely.
~Citizens automatically trust every decision#Incorrect. Lack of legitimacy reduces trust.
~Authority becomes stronger because people disagree#Incorrect. Disagreement does not automatically strengthen authority.
~Rules no longer matter in society#Incorrect. Rules may still exist even if legitimacy is weak.
}
